{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output we have global aggregates (count, mean, min, max, p95) for all component-KPI groups across the full available series, and the telemetry coverage for metric/trace/log is approximately 2024-01-19 00:06:00 to 00:30:00 UTC (within the incident window). The aggregate tables show no widespread log.error_count or trace.error_rate spikes; many p95 values are available per component-KPI. The candidate root-cause components (per task rules) are: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice. To follow the prescribed workflow we must now perform anomaly detection on metrics for only those candidate services using the global thresholds already computed (p95 per component-KPI from the full series). We should detect metric data points inside the incident window that breach their global thresholds and summarize counts, earliest breach time, max breach value and severity (max/threshold) per component-KPI to narrow down fault candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Using the full metric series, compute the global P95 threshold for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window [2024-01-19 00:03:59 UTC, 2024-01-19 00:33:59 UTC]. Restrict analysis to these candidate services: ['checkoutservice','currencyservice','emailservice','productcatalogservice','recommendationservice']. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in that subset, find rows in the incident window where value >= global_P95. Produce a compact summary table (store as metric_anom_summary) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as pd.Timestamp UTC), max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95. Return only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count descending, limit to top 20. Also return the total number of metric rows in the incident window for the candidate services (single integer)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric anomaly summary shows mostly small-magnitude breaches. Many groups (diskio/error) have p95==0 and are not actionable; some socket groups are constant at threshold. The most meaningful metric anomalies (severity >1 and non-zero thresholds) are concentrated in checkoutservice (cpu, latency-50/90, mem, workload, socket) and currencyservice (latency-50/90, mem), with a small mem exceedance in emailservice. These breaches are few and modest in severity (near 1.00–1.11). According to the workflow, we should now use traces to decide which of these service-level faults is the likely root cause (use traces to find the last faulty service in a call chain). We therefore need a compact trace-level anomaly summary for the candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice) within the incident window to see which services show trace-duration or error-rate anomalies, and whether they are downstream of others.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Using the full trace series, compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window [2024-01-19 00:03:59 UTC, 2024-01-19 00:33:59 UTC]. Restrict to candidate services: ['checkoutservice','currencyservice','emailservice']. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in that subset, find rows in the incident window where value >= global_p95. Produce a compact summary table (store as trace_anom_summary) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (as pd.Timestamp UTC), max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95. Return only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count descending, limit to top 20. Also return the total number of trace rows in the incident window for the candidate services (single integer)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace analysis for the incident window. Metrics show a few small-magnitude, short-lived exceedances concentrated in checkoutservice (cpu, latency-50/90, mem, workload, socket) and currencyservice (latency-50/90, mem); emailservice has a small memory bump. Traces show small, short row_count increases for checkoutservice (and small row_count bumps for emailservice), while most trace error_rate values are 0 (non-actionable). According to the workflow, traces suggest checkoutservice is the most downstream faulty service in call chains with meaningful anomalies, but the metric severity is modest. To localize the root cause reason (CPU/memory/disk/network/socket), we must now analyze logs for the possible root-cause services (per task rules): checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice. We should detect both high log KPIs (>= global P95) and low traffic KPIs (<= global P5) within the incident window to capture spikes or sudden drops. Also check error_logs for any messages in the window for those services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. For log.csv: using the full series compute global P95 and global P5 for each (cmdb_id, log_name). Then filter log.csv to the incident window [2024-01-19 00:03:59 UTC, 2024-01-19 00:33:59 UTC] and restrict to these services: ['checkoutservice','currencyservice','emailservice','productcatalogservice','recommendationservice']. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce two compact anomaly summaries:\n1) High anomalies (value >= global_p95): columns cmdb_id, log_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value/global_p95.\n2) Low anomalies (value <= global_p5): columns cmdb_id, log_name, global_p5, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), min_anomaly_value, drop_ratio = global_p5/min_anomaly_value.\nReturn only rows with anomaly_count > 0, sorted by anomaly_count desc, limit combined returned rows to top 20. Also return: total number of log rows in the incident window for the candidate services (single integer), and the subset of error_logs.csv rows within the incident window for those services (timestamp, cmdb_id, message), limit to top 20 if any."
}

